s and structures continued to shape young artists' engagement with both space and selfhood and occupied the minds of figures looking to reform the nation. In magnifying this fleeting moment, Lee provides a new historical foundation for the unprecedented global exposure of contemporary Chinese art today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCommunism and artzChinay20th century. 0aCommunist aesthetics. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520399280?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520399280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520399280/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles